Soil morphology is based on local topographic orientation. Soils within depressions are characterized by poorly drained clay material while the upslope soils are better drained. All soils are dominantly Clarion-Nicollet-Webster, fine textured with moderate to high organic matter content.

Soils have been subjected to mixing by windthrows, burrowing animals and earthworm activity, and frost action. Mottling and saturated soils were observed between 50 and 100 cm below the surface at different times during the year in these somewhat poorly drained soils.
